=== The Biopsychosocial Model as Asymmetry Engine

Schomerus et al.\ identify a structural weakness in how the biopsychosocial (BPS) model is applied to conditions with unknown pathophysiology. When the "bio" component is undefined—as in ME/CFS, where useful individual-level biomarkers do not exist—the model creates an asymmetry in what can be proven: psychological and social factors can always be proposed but never disproven, while the unspecified biological component provides no constraint on psychological attribution. The BPS model does not itself specify which factor causes what or how strongly; it is a framework for generating hypotheses, not a model that yields falsifiable predictions (predictions that could be proven wrong). In practice, however, it has functioned as a justification for psychological attributions that are protected from empirical challenge by the very uncertainty they exploit.

This critique is consistent with broader concerns about "concept creep" in psychiatry—the expansion of diagnostic categories to encompass normal distress—and about the use of psychiatric diagnosis as a "residual category" (a label used for anything not otherwise explained) for medically unexplained symptoms (Section @sec:diagnostic-controversies). The issue is not whether comorbid psychiatric conditions exist (they do, at increased prevalence) but whether psychiatric framing of the *primary illness* is justified when the only evidence for it is the absence of a known biomarker. Co-occurrence is not causation: the fact that ME/CFS produces psychiatric comorbidity does not justify attributing ME/CFS chronicity to psychological processes.
